---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
import Sample from '../../components/Sample.astro';
---
<Base title="The Hierarchy of Presence" section={5}>
  <article class="prose">

    <SectionHeader
      n={5}
      title="The Hierarchy of Presence"
      meta="~400 words · 1 interactive sample"
    />

    <p>
      A layout is an argument. Every width choice, every margin, every
      alignment decision is a claim about what matters and by how much.
      In a conversational interface, three things need to coexist: the
      place where you write, the place where you read, and the chrome
      that connects them. How these three things relate to each other
      determines the character of the entire experience.
    </p>

    <p>
      Generous inputs are psychologically important. A small input field
      signals "brief answers expected." A taller, full-width field with
      soft padding signals "take your time, say what you mean." The field
      doesn't need to be enormous — it needs to feel welcoming. That's a
      quality achieved by proportionality and whitespace, not raw size.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      The input box is generous — it signals "you are welcome to say a lot
      here." The response column is constrained — it signals "this is for
      reading, not scanning." Controls recede. Content leads.
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      The response column constraint is the more counterintuitive choice.
      Making the reading area narrower feels like removing real estate.
      In practice, it increases reading speed and comprehension. Line lengths
      above 75 characters force more lateral eye movement, which increases
      the cognitive effort required to track lines. The 640px constraint
      produces roughly 65–70 characters per line at body size — inside the
      optimal range.
    </p>

    <Sample label="Interactive sample — annotated layout diagram">
      <div style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 12px;">

        <!-- Layout mockup -->
        <div style="background: #fdf8f2; border-radius: 8px; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; padding: 16px; position: relative; overflow: hidden;">

          <!-- Header bar -->
          <div style="height: 28px; background: #f7f0e6; border-radius: 5px; margin-bottom: 12px; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; display: flex; align-items: center; padding: 0 10px; gap: 6px;">
            <div style="font-size: 10px; color: #a08060; flex: 1;">wordmark</div>
            <div style="display: flex; gap: 4px;">
              <div style="width: 16px; height: 3px; background: #c9956a; border-radius: 2px;"></div>
              <div style="width: 16px; height: 3px; background: #c9956a; border-radius: 2px;"></div>
              <div style="width: 16px; height: 3px; background: #e8c9a0; border-radius: 2px;"></div>
              <div style="width: 16px; height: 3px; background: #f0e6d8; border-radius: 2px;"></div>
              <div style="width: 16px; height: 3px; background: #f0e6d8; border-radius: 2px;"></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Content column (reading area) -->
          <div style="max-width: 280px; margin: 0 auto; position: relative;">
            <!-- Annotation callout left -->
            <div style="position: absolute; left: -110px; top: 8px; width: 96px; text-align: right;">
              <div style="font-size: 10px; color: #b07d5c; line-height: 1.4;">max-width<br/>640px</div>
              <div style="height: 1px; background: #e8c9a0; margin-top: 4px;"></div>
            </div>

            <!-- Section number -->
            <div style="font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif; font-size: 32px; color: #c8ad94; line-height: 1; margin-bottom: 4px;">01</div>
            <!-- Title -->
            <div style="font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif; font-size: 16px; color: #2d1f0e; margin-bottom: 8px;">Section Title</div>
            <!-- Body lines -->
            <div style="height: 8px; background: #e4d9cc; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 4px;"></div>
            <div style="height: 8px; background: #e4d9cc; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 4px; width: 92%;"></div>
            <div style="height: 8px; background: #e4d9cc; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 4px;"></div>
            <div style="height: 8px; background: #e4d9cc; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 4px; width: 80%;"></div>
            <div style="height: 8px; background: #e4d9cc; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 12px; width: 65%;"></div>

            <!-- Pull quote -->
            <div style="border-left: 2px solid #b07d5c; padding-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 12px;">
              <div style="height: 7px; background: #d4b896; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 3px; width: 90%;"></div>
              <div style="height: 7px; background: #d4b896; border-radius: 2px; width: 75%;"></div>
            </div>

            <!-- More body -->
            <div style="height: 8px; background: #e4d9cc; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 4px;"></div>
            <div style="height: 8px; background: #e4d9cc; border-radius: 2px; margin-bottom: 4px; width: 88%;"></div>

            <!-- Annotation callout right -->
            <div style="position: absolute; right: -116px; top: 120px; width: 100px; text-align: left;">
              <div style="height: 1px; background: #e8c9a0; margin-bottom: 4px;"></div>
              <div style="font-size: 10px; color: #b07d5c; line-height: 1.4;">serif for content<br/>sans for chrome</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Input area -->
          <div style="max-width: 280px; margin: 12px auto 0; background: #f7f0e6; border-radius: 6px; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; padding: 8px 10px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between;">
            <div style="font-size: 11px; color: #c8ad94; font-style: italic; font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif;">Say anything…</div>
            <div style="width: 20px; height: 20px; background: #c9956a; border-radius: 4px;"></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="display: flex; gap: 16px; margin-top: 12px; color: #a08060; flex-wrap: wrap;">
          <span>◆ Reading column: 640px</span>
          <span>◆ Generous input, constrained output</span>
          <span>◆ Controls recede</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Sample>

    <Annotation label="On whitespace">
      The margins outside the reading column are not wasted space.
      They create peripheral emptiness that reduces the brain's tendency
      to scan. When there's nothing to the left or right, the eye stays
      on the text. This is why physical books have generous margins even
      when the economics of paper argue against them.
    </Annotation>

    <h2>The numbers behind the comfort</h2>

    <p>
      Reading comfort isn't subjective. It's the aggregate of several
      measurable decisions that interact: font size, line height, column
      width, and paragraph spacing. Change any one without adjusting the
      others and the whole system degrades. These aren't independent
      choices — they're a set of interdependent constraints that either
      hold together or fall apart together.
    </p>

    <p>
      Body size at 17px sits one step above the browser default of 16px.
      That single pixel reduces the effort of resolving letterforms,
      particularly on high-resolution screens where 16px can start to feel
      small without quite feeling wrong. Line height at 1.85 is generous
      by UI standards — most interfaces run 1.4 to 1.5 — and intentionally
      so. This is a reading tool, not a dashboard. The extra leading creates
      air between lines that lets the eye return from the end of one line
      to the beginning of the next without losing its place. That return
      sweep is happening hundreds of times per reading session. Every
      pixel of leading is doing work.
    </p>

    <p>
      The 640px column at 17px Lora produces roughly 65–70 characters per
      line. This sits inside the range where lateral eye movement is
      efficient and line-tracking becomes automatic. Exceed 80 characters
      and the return sweep grows unreliable — the eye lands a line too
      high or too low, and the reader loses their place. Drop below 45
      and the constant line-breaks start to fragment thought before it
      can complete. Paragraph spacing at 1.4em signals a new idea without
      carving a gap large enough to feel like a section boundary.
    </p>

    <p>
      The reason these values live as tokens — <code>--text-body</code>,
      <code>--leading-body</code>, <code>--col-prose</code> — rather than
      hard-coded numbers is that they encode relationships, not just values.
      The moment font size changes, line height and column width need to
      be reconsidered. Token names make that dependency visible. A designer
      reading <code>--leading-body</code> knows this value is coupled to
      body copy specifically, and that changing it has consequences
      throughout the reading experience.
    </p>

    <Sample label="Comparison — compressed vs. comfortable reading conditions">
      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 16px; font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif;">

        <!-- Compressed -->
        <div>
          <div style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: #a08060; margin-bottom: 8px;">Compressed</div>
          <div style="background: #f7f0e6; border-radius: 6px; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; padding: 14px; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; color: #4a3728;">
            <p style="margin: 0 0 0.6em;">Most AI interfaces optimized for feature visibility over cognitive flow. They dressed up the machine instead of hiding it.</p>
            <p style="margin: 0 0 0.6em;">The result is an interface that constantly reminds you it is software — that it exists between you and the thought you were trying to have.</p>
            <p style="margin: 0;">Contrast this with an interface that disappears.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-top: 8px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #c8ad94;">16px · line-height 1.4 · unconstrained width</div>
        </div>

        <!-- Comfortable -->
        <div>
          <div style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: #8b6345; margin-bottom: 8px; font-weight: 500;">Comfortable ✓</div>
          <div style="background: #fdf3e8; border-radius: 6px; border: 0.5px solid #e8c9a0; padding: 14px; font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.85; color: #4a3728;">
            <p style="margin: 0 0 1.4em;">Most AI interfaces optimized for feature visibility over cognitive flow. They dressed up the machine instead of hiding it.</p>
            <p style="margin: 0 0 1.4em;">The result is an interface that constantly reminds you it is software — that it exists between you and the thought you were trying to have.</p>
            <p style="margin: 0;">Contrast this with an interface that disappears.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-top: 8px; font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; color: #8b6345;">17px · line-height 1.85 · 640px column</div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </Sample>

    <p>
      The hierarchy of presence is, ultimately, an argument about trust.
      When the layout signals that reading is the primary activity — through
      constrained columns, generous spacing, receding chrome — it tells the
      user: your attention is the most valuable thing here, and we've
      organized everything around protecting it. That's not a layout choice.
      It's a promise.
    </p>

  </article>
</Base>
